    <h2>How many Terabytes in a Petabyte</h2>
<p><strong>Petabyte (PB)</strong> is a digital information measurement unit=
 used to represent quite large amounts of information like monthly or annua=
l digital information exchange between some websites, or measuring the size=
 of some digital archives of large websites, etc. It is interesting that re=
cently scientists came up with the theory that a human brain can store data=
 of up to 2.5 PB. According to the SI standards, one petabyte is equal to 1=
,000 terabytes or 10<sup>15</sup> bytes. This unit is extensively used in t=
elecommunication, large data storage systems, cloud backup, computer games,=
 and many other related fields.</p>    <p><strong>1 Petabyte is equal to 10=
00 terabytes</strong> =3D 10<sup>3</sup> terabytes in base 10 (decimal) in =
SI.<br>
        <strong>1 Petabyte is also equal to 1024 terabytes</strong> =3D 2<s=
up>10</sup> terabytes in base 2 (binary) system.</p>
    <div class=3D"row">
        <div class=3D"col-6">
            <div class=3D"padding10">
                <h2>Petabytes</h2>
                    <p><strong>Terabyte (TB)</strong> is a digital informat=
ion measurement unit which is going to be extensively used in the nearest f=
uture for measuring the size of computer RAM, etc., but now it is used for =
measuring the amount of digital information in online libraries, digital ar=
chives, and so on. 1 terabyte is equal to 1000 gigabytes, or 10<sup>12</sup=
> bytes. However, in terms of information technology or computer science, 1=
 TB is 2<sup>40</sup> or 1024<sup>4</sup> bytes, which is equal to 1,099,51=
1,627,776 bytes.</p>                <pre><strong>Petabyte in SI and base 10=
 (decimal)</strong>
1 Petabyte =3D 1000<sup>5</sup> bytes
1 Petabyte =3D 1,000,000,000,000,000 bytes
<strong>Petabyte in base 2 (binary)</strong>
1 Petabyte =3D 2<sup>50</sup> bytes
1 Petabyte =3D 1024<sup>5</sup> bytes
1 Petabyte =3D 1,125,899,906,842,624 bytes
                </pre>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class=3D"col-6">
            <div class=3D"padding10">
                <h2>Terabytes</h2>
                <pre><strong>Terabyte in SI and base 10 (decimal)</strong>
1 Terabyte =3D 1000<sup>4</sup> bytes
1 Terabyte =3D 1,000,000,000,000 bytes
<strong>Terabyte in base 2 (binary)</strong>
1 Terabyte =3D 2<sup>40</sup> bytes
1 Terabyte =3D 1024<sup>4</sup> bytes
1 Terabyte =3D 1,099,511,627,776 bytes
                </pre>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class=3D"row">
        <div class=3D"col-6">
            <div class=3D"padding10">
                <h3>How to Calculate Petabytes to Terabytes</h3>
                <pre><strong>Petabyte in SI</strong>
1 Petabyte =3D 1000<sup>5</sup> bytes
We know that 1TB =3D 1000<sup>4</sup> bytes, so
1 byte =3D 1000<sup>-4</sup> terabytes
putting 1 byte in petabyte equation;
1 Petabyte =3D 1000<sup>5</sup> * 1000<sup>-4</sup> TB
1 Petabyte =3D 1000<sup>1</sup> Terabytes
1 Petabyte =3D 1000 Terabytes
                </pre>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class=3D"col-6">
            <div class=3D"padding10">
                <h3>PB to TB in Base 2</h3>
                <pre><strong>Petabyte in base 2</strong>
1 Petabyte =3D 2<sup>50</sup> bytes
1 Petabyte =3D 1024<sup>5</sup> bytes
1 byte =3D 1024<sup>-5</sup> TB
1 Petabyte =3D 1024<sup>5</sup> * 1024<sup>-4</sup> TB
1 Petabyte =3D 1024<sup>1</sup> Terabytes
1 Petabyte =3D 2<sup>10</sup> Terabytes
1 Petabyte =3D 1024 Terabytes
                </pre>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
